## Creating a new job
- Click **Create job **in the toolbar.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Select the **Account **for which to create the new job. You may start typing the name of the account to filter the list.

- Select the required On-Demand **Workflow **resource. You may start typing the name of the workflow to filter the list.

- Select the input **File **to upload.

- Click **Create**. The new on-demand job is now visible in the **Jobs **table.

> **Note**

The **Create job **button is only enabled if no jobs are selected.

## Managing jobs
Select one or more jobs to view the available actions.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> **Note**

Actions that are available on individual files may not be available on a multiple selection (for example, the **Inspect **action).

**Icon**

**Action**

**Description**

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[**Download content**](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-on-demand-jobs-managing-jobs#downloading-the-request-response-and-intermediate-outputs-of-a-job)

Download the job's request and response (if available), and the outputs of all intermediate tasks.

The content is downloaded as a ZIP file, that includes a folder for the request and a folder for the response, containing all input and output files in plain format.

> **Important**

The input file provided with the Request may have a different name in the downloaded package (for example *data.xml *or *origin*) instead of the original filename.

> **Note**

The option to save the outputs of all intermediate tasks for troubleshooting purposes is enabled by default; it can be configured in the deployment phase. For more information, see: [On-Demand Workflow Resource Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/on-demand-workflow-resource-reference).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[**Download logs**](#)

Download the the job's logs.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[**Inspect**](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-on-demand-jobs-managing-jobs#inspecting-a-job)

Open the **Inspect **panel to view more information on the job.

> **Tip**

You may also hover on the name of a job, click on the **... **icon that appears, and select one of the available actions from the context menu. For example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Downloading the request, response and intermediate outputs of a job
- Hover your mouse pointer on the row corresponding to a job. The **... **(**More**) icon appears; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Select **Download content **from the menu to save a copy of the request and (if available) the response of the selected job, and also the outputs of all intermediate tasks, to your local filesystem.

> **Note**

If the job was completed successfully, the downloaded file will contain the request and response and also the outputs of all intermediate tasks, organized in folders. Otherwise, the response will not be present.

If the job was suspended due to a malformed request, the downloaded file (filename *malformed request*) will contain the request data in a file for the native compatibility level, and in a folder for the DP2 compatibility level.

The job's request, response and output files are downloaded in ZIP format; for example: *job-2554.zip*.

### Downloading the job's logs
- Select a job.

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Download logs**) to save the job's log files to your local filesystem.

> **Note**

The job's logs are downloaded in plain text format; for example: *job-12499.logs.txt*.

> **Important**

If the job's logs are not ready yet, the system displays a notification message instead of downloading an empty file.

### Inspecting a job
The **Inspect **panel provides more information on the status and properties of the selected job, including details on the individual tasks and on the corresponding workflow.

- Select a job.

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Inspect**), or click on the name of the job.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> **Note**

For more information, see: [Doxee Platform On-Demand Jobs - Inspect Panel](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-on-demand-jobs-inspect-panel), section "Inspecting a job".
